<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-04-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-04-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="209" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d209">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Lord
                                    <persName type="to">Pauncefote</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State.</hi><lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-04-05"><hi rend="italic">April 5,
                                1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2130.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your excellency’s note, No. 81, of the 28th ultimo, and to
                            inform you in <pb facs="0295" n="215" xml:id="pg_215"/> reply that
                            Rear-Admiral George C. Remey, commander in chief, United States naval
                            force, Asiatic Station, will proceed to Melbourne with the flagship <hi rend="italic">Brooklyn</hi> upon the occasion of the visit of their
                            royal hignesses the Duke and Duchess of Cornwall and York and the
                            opening of the Australian Parliament.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>